@NODE "Requirements"

System Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  · An Amiga with at least a 68020 processor

  · Miami Deluxe

  · ShapeShifter or Fusion 3.2 running Open Transport TCP 1.1 or higher
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Install"

The Installation Procedure
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  In this archive you will find the following files

  vlink.device.020-030
  vlink.device.040
  vlink.device.060
  vlinkmirror.device.020-030
  vlinkmirror.device.040
  vlinkmirror.device.060

  Simply copy the appropriate vlink.device and vlinkmirror.device to the
  DEVS:Networks directory. If DEVS: does not contain a Networks directory,
  then you will have to create it first.

  For example, if your Amiga has a 68060 processor, you would install the
  appropriate files by issuing the following commands from a shell.

  copy vlink.device.060 DEVS:Networks/vlink.device
  copy vlinkmirror.device.060 DEVS:Networks/vlinkmirror.device
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Setup"

Setting Up The Software
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  Setting up VirtualLink requires adding the proper hardware and interface
  definitions to Miami Deluxe and configuring ShapeShifter and MacTCP.
  Step-by-Step instructions are provided for doing this. If you follow these
  steps you should have no problem getting VirtualLink up and running.
  Networking gurus may wish to take liberties with the setup procedure and
  configure Miami Deluxe and MacTCP to their own tastes.


    @{" Miami Deluxe Setup " LINK "MiamiSetup"} Configuring Miami Deluxe

    @{" ShapeShifter Setup " LINK "SSSetup"} Configuring ShapeShifter

    @{" Fusion Setup       " LINK "FusionSetup"} Configuring Fusion

    @{" MacTCP Setup       " LINK "MacSetup"} Configuring the Macintosh

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MiamiSetup"

How To Configure Miami Deluxe
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  @{B}Create the hardware definition@{UB}
   1. Bring up the Miami Deluxe interface and go to the @{I}Hardware@{UI} page
   2. Click on the @{I}New@{UI} button
   3. From the @{I}Hardware Type@{UI} window click on the @{I}Ethernet@{UI} button
   4. Type @{B}VirtualLink@{UB} into the @{I}Name@{UI} field
   5. Verify that the @{I}Type@{UI} gadget is set to @{B}SANA-II driver@{UB}
   6. Click on the file requester button next to the @{I}Driver@{UI} field
   7. From the file requester select @{B}vlink.device@{UB} and click on OK
   8. Verify that the @{I}Driver@{UI} field contains @{B}DEVS:Networks/vlink.device@{UB}
   9. Click on the @{I}SANA-II parameters...@{UI} button
  10. Click on the @{I}Query device@{UI} button and then click OK
  11. At this point click OK to accept this hardware definition
  12. Verify that a new definition named @{B}VirtualLink@{UB} appears in the page

  @{B}Create the interface definition@{UB}
  13. Go to the @{I}Interfaces@{UI} page
  14. Click on the @{I}New@{UI} button
  15. Set the Interface type to @{I}Etherenet@{UI}
  16. Set the Interface to @{I}LAN@{UI}
  17. Click OK
  18. Select @{B}VirtualLink@{UB} from the window that pops up and click OK
  19. Set the IP address to 192.168.1.1
  20. Set the Netmask to 255.255.255.0
  21. Move the @{I}Gateway Pri@{UI} slider to the right so that it reads 1
  22. Set the Gateway to 192.168.1.254
  23. Move the @{I}Gateway Pri@{UI} slider back to the left so that it reads 0
  24. Click on the @{I}Events@{UI} button
  25. Click on the @{I}Auto-online@{UI} button so that it becomes checked
  26. Click OK
  27. At this point click OK to accept this Interface definition
  28. Verify that a new entry with the alias @{B}VirtualLink@{UB} appears in the page

  @{B}Activate routing@{UB}
  29. Go to the @{I}TCP/IP@{UI} page
  30. Click on the @{I}Gateway@{UI} gadget so that is becomes checked
  31. Click on the @{I}LAN-Connect...@{UI} button
  32. Set IP-NAT to @{I}internal@{UI}
  33. Verify that the FTP and IRC-DCC buttons are checked
  34. Click OK

  @{B}And finally@{UB}
  35. Save these settings so you don't have to go through this again
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SSSetup"

How To Configure ShapeShifter
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  1. Bring up the ShapeShifter Settings interface
  2. Click on the @{I}Network...@{UI} button
  3. On the @{I}Network Settings@{UI} window click on the @{I}Choose@{UI} button
  4. From the file requester select @{B}vlinkmirror.device@{UB} and click OK
  5. Verify that the driver field contains @{B}DEVS:Networks/vlinkmirror.device@{UB}
  6. Close the @{I}Network Settings@{UI} window
  7. Click on the @{I}Save@{UI} button to save the settings
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FusionSetup"

How To Configure Fusion
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  1. Go to the @{I}Peripherals@{UI} page
  2. Click on the @{I}Network@{UI} button
  3. Click on the file requester button
  4. From the file requester select @{B}vlinkmirror.device@{UB} and click LOAD
  5. Verify that the driver field contains @{B}vlinkmirror.device@{UB}
  6. Click the @{I}Exit@{UI} button
  7. Be sure to save the settings
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MacSetup"

How To Configure MacTCP
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  1. Bring up the TCP/IP control panel
  2. Set the @{I}Connect via selection@{UI} pop-up to @{I}Ethernet@{UI}
  3. Set the @{I}Configure selection@{UI} pop-up to @{I}Manually@{UI}
  4. Set the IP Address to 192.168.1.2
  5. Set the Subnet mask to 255.255.255.0
  6. Set the Router address to 192.168.1.1
  7. Set the @{I}Name server addr@{UI} field to your provider's DNS address
  8. Add your provider's domain name to the @{I}Search domains@{UI} field
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Notes"

Random Thoughts
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  · One other possible use for VirtualLink is as a testing tool for network
    application developers

  · The version of MacTCP that comes with MacOS 7.5.x is unstable and
    VirtualLink seems to aggravate it. If you are running MacOS 7.5 and
    are having trouble with VirtualLink, try installing the latest version
    of Open Transport TCP. This is available from Apple's FTP site.

  · I didn't see a need to write an installer script since the installation
    procedure is simply a matter of copying two files from one directory to
    another.

  · VirtualLink should work with AmiTCP. Unfortunately, I don't have AmiTCP
    so I haven't been able to test this. I would be interested in hearing
    from anyone who is using VirtualLink with AmiTCP.

  · VirtualLink should work with Miami 3.2 but since Miami 3.2 doesn't
    support multiple interfaces, the usefulness of such a setup would be
    limited.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "History"

VirtualLink Revision History
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

  Version 1.2 7/20/00

  · Corrected the MTU size reported by the device.

  · Packets are now written to and read from the virtual wire by the same
    task. This should improve performance since now a reader doesn't have
    to wait for an extra task switch in order to get a packet.


  Version 1.1 12/21/99

  · Fixed a bug that could cause a crash if VirtualLink is accessed without
    both devices resident.


  Version 1.0  12/5/99

  · First public release.
@ENDNODE

